      },
      "date": "2012-03-31 12:25:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nBruce,\n\nMaybe I am not understanding the nature of the problem exactly.  Do you have an example of the problem this code is causing?  Or how I could see an example locally?  If I configure a lustre tree and then run \"make rpms\", what is the breakage I am looking for?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "550962096b7f4e01f6867e3d20fbe98a4518a883",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 221,
        "name": "Bruce Korb",
        "email": "bruce_korb@xyratex.com",
        "username": "bkorb",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-02 14:10:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nTo see the problem, you must first induce an error in a subdirectory build.  One way of doing this is to not provide a value for BUILD_TESTS.  That will cause a scripting failure.  That issue was fixed.  So:\n\n1. That should not have been a failure in the first place.\n    When one writes a make file for a subdirectory, they should not\n    be required to scrutinize the long, convoluted \"toplevel\" included\n    makefile for obscure variables that must be set \"true\" or \"false\".\n    After all, only one subdirectory requires that BUILD_TESTS be\n    set true, yet its needs force recognition in all other subdirs.\n\n2. When there is a failure due to this or any other issue, the build\n    must stop.  Without this patch, it continues as if there were nothing\n   wrong and I had to laboriously hunt down the cause. (Which was #1\n   above, but has since been fixed without fixing the infrastructure\n   problem.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "53142700c2941f20d9e8bc81512054c1587157d6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 116,
        "name": "Brian J. Murrell",
        "email": "brian.murrell@intel.com",
        "username": "brian",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-02 16:07:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI'm sorry but I'm not sure I'm following.  Is there a set of steps I can take with current lustre-release master to see the failure you are addressing here?  i.e. would simply:\n\n$ ./configure ...\n$ make rpms\n\ndemonstrate the failure?  Do I need any particular configure flags?\n\nAlternatively you said there was an issue that was already fixed that triggered the problems in this patch.  Can you point me at that issue so that I can better understand the problem space here?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1083118c813ce273e11a55e196d134ebec6346cf",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 221,
        "name": "Bruce Korb",
        "email": "bruce_korb@xyratex.com",
        "username": "bkorb",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-04-02 20:25:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThis will complete successfully:\n\n$ cd $(git rev-parse --git-dir)/..\n$ sed -i \"/^BUILD_TESTS/s/^/# /\" ldiskfs/autoMakefile.am\n$ bash ./autogen\n$ configure\n$ make\n$ make rpms\n\nbut not really.\nThe ./autoMakefile.am will source \"build/autoMakefile.am.toplevel\"\nand go through a subdirectory loop that will not notice that when\nthe rpms-real rule gets invoked in the subdirectory, it chokes and dies.\nIt chokes and dies because BUILD_TESTS is undefined triggering a\nshell syntax error.  But it could be any other failure, too.\n\n1. Failing to define BUILD_TESTS should not lead to an error because\n    it is imposing implementation details to various lustre components\n    that do not really need to know that stuff.  If you really have to\n    make the make fail because someone neglected to add BUILD_TESTS\n    values (as was the case a few weeks ago), then at least make the\n   error comprehensible instead of a shell syntax error failure.\n\n2. If there is a subdirectory failure, then the make process must stop.\n    The current setup marches on as if there is nothing awry.  There\n    are two approaches to fixing it, and I chose one of them.\n\n   a) use this syntax when using a subshell in a make file:\n        ( cd somewhere ; do-some-stuff ) || false\n      if there is a failure, the subshell exits non-zero and runs the \"false\" command.\n      That will tell the shell to exit if \"set -e\" has been utilized.\n      If you do not use the \"|| false\" the shell *WILL* *NOT* *EXIT*\n      even though \"set -e\" has been specified.\n\n   b) use this syntax, avoiding a subshell make entirely\n       (this is what I chose):\n\n        { cd somewhere ; do-some-stuff ; cd - }",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "20584606ba26a44488a4ff64892e3f10c11a3b7f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-04-03 15:51:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI tend to agree with Bruce's logic here - the need to define BUILD_TESTS and BUILD_SERVER should not be imposed on all of the sub-autoMakefiles if they don't really care about them.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
